place_name: El Grito Mexican Taqueria Mountjoy Square
formatted_address: 20 Mountjoy Square E, Mountjoy, Dublin, D01 K3T1, Ireland
review_text: Had been to El Grito recently and loved it! The nachos were the highlight - tasty, filling, and full of flavor. The chimichanga was a great addition too, really delicious and satisfying. The chicken and Mexican rice soup with crispy nachos was hearty and comforting. Washed it all down with a refreshing Mexican mojito. The place has a lovely authentic Mexican vibe, and the staff were super cheerful and friendly. Great food, great atmosphere ,will definitely be back! 🌮✨

place_name: El Grito Mexican Taqueria Mountjoy Square
formatted_address: 20 Mountjoy Square E, Mountjoy, Dublin, D01 K3T1, Ireland
review_text:
I’ve just been to this Mexican restaurant in the middle of nowhere, and honestly, it blew me away. From the moment you walk in, the atmosphere, the music, the smells, the sounds, and the people make it feel absolutely mesmerizing.

Looking at the menu, I genuinely felt like I was back in Mexico. Every dish was bursting with flavor—tasty, fresh, and authentic. The guacamole was incredible, and the cocktail was spot on.

While I was there, I noticed two birthday parties being celebrated, and the staff were just amazing—so happy, welcoming, and full of energy. You can tell they really enjoy what they do.

It’s not a massive restaurant, but maybe that’s what makes it so special. It’s a hidden gem. If you want real Mexican food and the feeling of being in Mexico without leaving town, you need to visit this place.
Plus we were welcomed without a reservation !!!!!

place_name: El Grito Mexican Taqueria Mountjoy Square
formatted_address: 20 Mountjoy Square E, Mountjoy, Dublin, D01 K3T1, Ireland
review_text:
El Grito is a fantastic Mexican restaurant in Dublin!
The atmosphere is warm and welcoming, with charming décor that makes you feel right at home. The staff are always smiling and friendly, which adds to the pleasant experience.

I had a delicious burrito, paired with a Michelada — absolutely amazing!
The food is full of authentic flavors, the service is quick and efficient, and prices are fair and perfectly aligned with the quality offered. Highly recommended!

review_text:
We had a lovely first visit to your restaurant. The vibe was great, and the staff were very attentive. As it was my first time trying the dish I ordered, I don't feel I can fairly comment on the food itself.

The only thing that gave me pause was the 10% mandatory service charge for group of four or more.I personally prefer the freedom to leave a tip based on the service experience. This policy was the main reason for my 3-star rating on this occasion. Perhaps it's just my lack of familiarity with this practice.

formatted_address: 60-61 Middle Abbey St, North City, Dublin 1, D01 Y4N8, Ireland
review_text:
To start with the positive, the staff were really friendly.

Unfortunately, for me, it was a rip-off. My burger was cold and it came with a pile of lettuce and a few pieces of chopped tomato as an excuse for a salad. No dressing or anything. In the photo, you’ll see there are some beans that my mate gave me in sympathy.

The waiter offered to replace it straight away, so no complaints about the wait staff.

The burger itself was straight out of the freezer. It cost 14€, which is outrageous. Won’t be returning.

formatted_address: 60-61 Middle Abbey St, North City, Dublin 1, D01 Y4N8, Ireland
review_text:
I was looking forward to dining at Kalabasa Market, but my experience left quite a bit to be desired.
It felt like seating was reserved for those who personally knew the staff—walk-ins like us were left waiting while others were quickly accommodated.
Once we were finally seated, the table was still covered in crumbs and spills from previous guests. Even after 20 minutes, no one came to clean it, despite us asking three times.
Service was frustratingly slow, and as a non-Spanish speaker, I felt somewhat dismissed rather than welcomed.
It’s a shame, because the place has potential.
I hope they consider improving accessibility, hospitality, and basic service for all guests.

formatted_address: Unit 4, Block C, Point campus, North Wall, Dublin, D01 V2K7, Ireland
review_text:
I’ve been here twice.
First time - super friendly staff, substantial amount of meat in the burrito, very tasty. Thought I’d found a new favourite burrito place.
Second time - where is my chicken and chorizo? 😢 A tiny bit of chicken, couldn’t see any chorizo, mostly rice which was bland. Very disappointed. Bizarrely, the staff member on check out would only stamp my loyalty card once despite buying two burrito meals. I was told the policy is one stamp per order. Not that it’s a concern as I can’t imagine I’ll be back unless it’s the staff from my first visit the week previous.
Nice little seating area. They charge extra for things I’d consider basic like cheese.

formatted_address: Upstairs, 62 Mary St, North City, Dublin 1, D01 XP94, Ireland
review_text:
It was our first time at Pickasitos and we were genuinely impressed. The food was so fresh and full of flavour. Portions are big, but the prices feel really fair for what you get, so it ends up being great value.

The nachos were a standout. Plenty of guac (which we loved) and the cheese was spread throughout, not just dumped on the top few chips like you get in a lot of places. The tacos were packed with flavour, and the pulled beef burrito was really juicy.  We left super full and happy!! Would definitely recommend.

formatted_address: Upstairs, 62 Mary St, North City, Dublin 1, D01 XP94, Ireland
review_text:
Pickosito’s food never disappoints!
You can taste it’s fresh and made with love.
We always get the slow cooked beef taco with extra guacamole (although it’s very little guacamole for 2€), quesadillas and horchata.

The service is good, but the first time you come it’s a bit confusing. Meaning, you don’t really understand that you need to self serve, get your own menu then order at the counter. But with experience, you get there fast. A bit more emphasis on communicating this to new customers would help increase the overall experience.

The atmosphere is great if you want a place that is authentic. Seeing the chef work the dough, the piñatas, fun facts displayed on posters adds to the Mexican feel.

I definitely recommend checking this place and coming back to try new things.

formatted_address: 7 South Great George's Street, Dublin 2, D02 EV81, Ireland
review_text:
We booked for a large group of nine, and while our table was a bit of a squeeze, the lively atmosphere made up for the 'cosy' seating.

The menu is packed with tempting options, but my eyes were set on the legendary Chimichanga. We kicked things off with some spicy chicken wings and nachos. They were tasty and arrived quickly.

When the Chimichanga arrived, it was a true 'Man vs. Food' moment. This colossal dish, stuffed with chicken, cheese, pinto beans, jalapeños, and guacamole, was as delicious as it was huge. Not everyone at the table could conquer it, but the brave few who did earned some serious bragging rights. The cool, refreshing Margaritas were the perfect accompaniment to the challenge.

Just when we thought we couldn't manage another bite, we indulged in Acapulco's signature dessert: deep-fried ice cream with a homemade butterscotch sauce. It was a decadent and perfect end to the meal.

Overall, despite the snug table, Acapulco delivered a fantastic experience with food that impresses in both quantity and quality.

formatted_address: Unit 41/42, Blackrock Village Centre, Rock Hill, Blackrock, Dublin, A94 XH96, Ireland
review_text:
I had such a fantastic experience at Zambrero! The food was fresh, flavorful, and full of that vibrant energy you expect from great Mexican-inspired cuisine. Every bite felt wholesome yet indulgent, and the menu offered plenty of options to suit different tastes.

What truly made the visit memorable, though, was the outstanding service from Elton. He was welcoming, attentive, and genuinely enthusiastic about making sure everything was perfect. His friendly attitude and professionalism added so much warmth to the atmosphere, it felt less like a transaction and more like being looked after by someone who really cares.

Zambrero already stands out for its delicious food and social mission, but with team members like Elton, the experience goes above and beyond. Highly recommend both the restaurant and the incredible service!

formatted_address: Unit 41/42, Blackrock Village Centre, Rock Hill, Blackrock, Dublin, A94 XH96, Ireland
review_text:
Came in with high expectations and left very disappointed.

First off, the portion sizes. Keep in mind I came in the morning, so it's not busy and everything is fully stocked and ready.

I'm not joking when I say I got an actual teaspoon worth of pinto beans and maybe 2 tablespoons of rice on my burrito. I was immediately wondering where on earth the rest of my burrito was.

Next came the meat. Reasonably sized scoop of pork, but given how little rice and beans I got, I asked if I could get a little bit more pulled pork, to which I was told very bluntly I have to pay for that.

At least they were generous with the vegetables, but the very limited selection kind of threw me off - normally any burrito place I go to have twice the amount of options.

Then, the burrito itself. It really wasn't great. The rice and beans were essentially imperceptible, the pork was drenched in a horrendously sweet and artificial-tasting barbaque sauce (yet somehow the meat was still dry), and the overwhelming majority of the wrap was vegetables. Now granted, I got all the veg options on it (of which there are about 4) but ONLY because of how little rice and beans I was given.

The vegetables, like the pork, were also all horrifically sweet. I seriously think they must coat them with sugar.

The wrap was only very lightly warmed, so by the time I sat down and took a bite of the burrito, it was lukewarm at best.

To add to the underwhelming experience, my girlfriend's order of loaded nachos was a similar ordeal. Very light on all the ingredients, even the nachos themselves!  She had been to other Zambreros and gotten the same thing before, and said she had never had a plate that bare.

To top it all off, the issues with the staff. The lady who served us (one of the two there, although one was just on his laptop in the eating area) kept staring over at myself and my girlfriend and hiding when we looked over. She was also coughing all over the work area in the back without covering her mouth, and I assume that's the area where the food is prepared, making it even more disgusting and unhygienic.

Very disappointed with this place. I was expecting good things since it's located in such a affluent area. Real shame, since this has now put me off from visiting any other Zambreros in the future.

formatted_address: Castle House, 7 South Great George's Street, Dublin 2, D02 HX99, Ireland
review_text:
Ordered - CARNE ASADA (for two): 24 oz Côte de Boeuf, Black Beans, Pico de Gallo, Guacamole, Chimichurri, Elotes, Papas Fritas.
Everything was cooked to perfection, I'm usually a picky eater but I had some of everything — probably spurred on by the price I'd paid 😉 — and enjoyed it all! My date (who is Mexican) was similarly impressed with the food!
The beef was juicy and flavourful, the assorted bits on the plate were each well done and paired nicely with it, the fried potatoes were crispy on the outside and perfectly softened inside, and the corn (elotes) was okay — the smoky flavour was nice on it but there wasn't much to bite into (kernels didn't go very deep)
I had a house ginger beer and she had a pinky tuscadero, both tasted good!
There weren't any tables for two, so we were sat at the bar which was a little disappointing.
The decoration in the indoor dining area was fun and pretty authentic.
For me the music was playing just a little bit loud so it wasn't great for conversation, something the staff/management might review given that it was a Tuesday night and not a weekend.
All in all still a great experience and would go again with more people if the music was a little quieter.
We had been waiting to eat for a good few hours before arriving so we didn't wait to take a photo, photo credit to @867claireh on TripAdvisor.

review_text:
Taste is good, but it is extremely pricy.

The bowl as you can see in the photo is way smaller than any of the bowls of other competitors in Dublin, and the price is the same/higher.

Today I got a superbowl for a bit of extra meat and guess what? Cheese wasn’t included in that higher price, even though it is included with no cost in the normal bowl (cheaper version). So for the already small bowl with a bit of extra meat +cheese + guacamole I paid 14 euro!!! Sorry but this is extremely expensive for what you get.

Another tip to the management team. Use bigger bowls also so that people can mix the different ingredients together, because now this is impossible to do that without spilling everything out of the bowl.

review_text: I went with my family after seeing a good few people enjoying their meals, which tempted us to give it a try. We waited around 10 minutes for a table. The staff were lovely and very attentive. The food, however, wasn’t really our thing. There were quite a lot of spices, especially paprika, more than we’re used to in other Mexican restaurants. That said, the ingredients were fresh, particularly the guacamole. The tacos weren’t to our taste, so we couldn’t finish them. The quesadilla filling was nice, but again the paprika was a bit strong for us. They have a great selection of drinks. It might suit others more than us, but fair play to them and best of luck.

formatted_address: 3 Abbey Street Lower, North City, Dublin 1, D01 K6R2, Ireland
review_text:
Boojum - Abbey Street: Dublin's Ultimate Burrito Fix! 🇸🇪🫂☘️

If you’re craving a huge, satisfying, and flavour-packed Mexican feed in Dublin, Boojum on Abbey Street is essentially a local institution. It's the king of fast-casual Mexican food, giving you massive portions that are fantastic value for money. 🌯👑

The setup is classic assembly-line style, but the ingredients are far from standard fast food. Everything is made *fresh* daily—from the slow-cooked meats (the carnitas and chipotle chicken are customer favourites!) to the vibrant, punchy salsas. They even offer a terrifying-sounding but beloved **Naga salsa** for the truly brave. 🔥🌶️

The Highlights (The Feast):

* Size Matters: The burritos here are legendary. They are giant, tightly wrapped cylinders of Mexican rice, meat, beans, and fillings. You'll likely need to use a fork by the time you're halfway through, and you definitely won't be hungry afterwards. 💚
* Customization Heaven: You are the master chef here. You choose everything: burrito, bowl, or tacos; black or pinto beans; all the fresh toppings and salsas. This makes it a great spot for vegans and vegetarians too, with options like Vegan Chilli Beans and Pork Imitator fillings. 🥑🥦
* The Vibe: It’s centrally located right near O'Connell Street, so it's always buzzing with shoppers, students (hello, student discount!), and office workers. It’s loud, quick, and efficient—perfect for a satisfying lunch or a post-pub dinner.

While the service style is fast and occasional reports mention minor mix-ups (especially with delivery), the quality and sheer volume of the food keep people lining up. It’s a reliable, delicious, and budget-friendly win! 🙏🏻🕯✝️🇻🇦🕊

5/5 Stars! ⭐⭐⭐⭐

place_name: Vida's - Mexican Cantina and Cocktail Bar
formatted_address: 16 Sandyford Rd, Dundrum, Dublin, D16 X8W9, Ireland
review_text:
I have to say this place is a 10/10. I will admit I have a bias for Mexican food. It’s hard for me to leave with a bad taste in my mouth but this place is so good.

We unfortunately ate all the nachos and jalapeño poppers before I remembered to take a pic and started on the tacos too but it was so good.

The nachos we got the full portion and they’re big. I would’ve liked a bit more guac and pico de gallo but other than that very generous. Full of flavour. Even the tortilla chips you could see were covered in flavour. The guac and sour cream were super fresh as well as the pico de Gallo.

The jalapeño peppers were the best I’ve had so far. Most places do it wrong and get the jalapeño ruined or leave the skin but no spice or lack cheese or come soggy but these were served on top of a chipotle sauce I think and still were crispy. The cheese was delicious though I could’ve used a little more and the sauce was really nice with the jalapeño. Worked to cool your mouth a little.

The tacos were so good. I would’ve liked some more veg with them like pico de gallo cause they were protein heavy but the flavour was amazing. The sauce they came with was so good too. It was a smoky tomato flavour and I nearly would’ve drank it. They were so worth it.

Considering all we got the price wasn’t bad bar the drinks, €4 for small soft drinks is a rip. The staff were super friendly, checking in and making sure everything is ok. They definitely deserve a raise for their customer service skills. As well of the chefs for their cooking skills too of course. Delicious.

It was also quiet on a Sunday evening which was nice. Made for a nice atmosphere. Very chilled.

review_text:

formatted_address: 63 Mespil Rd, Dublin 4, D04 RX37, Ireland
review_text:
I usually have a great experience at this Boojum—the food is always excellent, and the staff are generally friendly. However, on 13 March 2025 at 18:04, I had a disappointing experience.

I was ordering for a friend, but there was a miscommunication about whether they wanted a bowl or a burrito. I paid for the bowl but realized the mistake after leaving. When I returned to request a swap to a burrito, the staff said it would cost €0.85, claiming the bowl contained more food.

I briefly left but returned within two minutes to clarify. A staff member initially said there would be no extra charge if the remaining food stayed in the store. We agreed, and they transferred the food to a wrap. However, after doing so, they suddenly insisted I had to pay the €0.85. When I questioned this, the staff member became aggressive, raising her voice and refusing to listen. Her attitude was unprofessional and unnecessarily rude.

Another employee stepped in, took ownership of the situation, and confirmed I didn’t need to pay. I later called another Boojum location, and they said pricing policies vary by store, but swapping from a burrito to a bowl typically incurs no extra charge.

This experience was disappointing. While it may have been a one-off, the staff member could have been more polite in their style of communication.
review_original_text:
I usually have a great experience at this Boojum—the food is always excellent, and the staff are generally friendly. However, on 13 March 2025 at 18:04, I had a disappointing experience.

I was ordering for a friend, but there was a miscommunication about whether they wanted a bowl or a burrito. I paid for the bowl but realized the mistake after leaving. When I returned to request a swap to a burrito, the staff said it would cost €0.85, claiming the bowl contained more food.

I briefly left but returned within two minutes to clarify. A staff member initially said there would be no extra charge if the remaining food stayed in the store. We agreed, and they transferred the food to a wrap. However, after doing so, they suddenly insisted I had to pay the €0.85. When I questioned this, the staff member became aggressive, raising her voice and refusing to listen. Her attitude was unprofessional and unnecessarily rude.

Another employee stepped in, took ownership of the situation, and confirmed I didn’t need to pay. I later called another Boojum location, and they said pricing policies vary by store, but swapping from a burrito to a bowl typically incurs no extra charge.

This experience was disappointing. While it may have been a one-off, the staff member could have been more polite in their style of communication.

formatted_address: 47, Ranelagh, Dublin 6, D06 HR84, Ireland
review_text:
Hands down the best Mexican fusion spot I’ve been to in Dublin. The service was absolutely stunning, and the food was on another level — every bite felt like a perfect mix of creativity and authenticity.

The atmosphere is spot on too: the soft, half-light gives it a romantic feel, making it an ideal place for a date night or simply to try something different from your usual spots. The music was perfectly chosen and at just the right volume — enough to set the mood without making you raise your voice, so you can enjoy your own conversation without overhearing everyone else’s.

And a big plus: it’s dog-friendly, which makes it such a refreshing and inclusive option in the city.

Highly recommend!

review_text:

A standout feature is the mandatory lightning-fast dining pace (relative to how slowly the food arrives), perfect if you’re searching for an excuse to cut the evening short. We were asked to leave within five minutes of our desserts hitting the table (desserts that took fifteen minutes to arrive and were impressively basic), and this came just five minutes after we were asked if we’d like another round of drinks.

formatted_address: Rere of 46, Clontarf Rd, Clontarf, Dublin 3, D03 A5X2, Ireland
review_text:
Tonight I went to Chubbys and tasted half their menu. Ooh, wooow! The atmosphere is cozy/professional/great. The staff is friendly and prompt. Everything about this place immediately tells you how good it is going to be.

Then the food... Just stop!! All the dishes were mouth watering and finger on lickin'. I started with a cocktail; Sichuan Cherry Manhattan, which was perfect. Then, in short order, there arrived such an array of flavour and tast that my mouth exploded with delight. Everything from simple corn on the cob - corn ribs, to lmab on charred flatbread with generous amounts of perfectly balanced toppings, to Indian tasty fried chicken and more, all was delicious. I went all the way beyond my capacity to a sweet and savory desert with chocolate, nuts, ice cream and butter scotch sauce. I don't even do this meal justice trying to describe it.

It is safe to say I absolutely recommend this place. You will be grateful for every bite from each if their dishes.

review_text: We had dinner here after reading the really positive review in the Irish Independant. The atmosphere was lively, the staff were absolutely excellent, friendly and helpful and the food was nice, just not the experience I expected it to be. The portion sizes for the pork roll and beef Mulita were not very big for the price (€12 and €11 respectively), and the garlic butter and parmesan fries, whilst a good size portion and tasty, were very expensive at €11.50!! Also, I do have an issue with restaurants charging €3.50 for a tiny 200ml Coca Cola. It's just too much! The nice service really did stand out though, cheers to lovely server Rob.

review_text:
The service and speed of food leaving the kitchen let it down during our visit. One attentive foh staff member who had little enthusiastic support on the day.

Food itself was only okay, some hits (lamb flatbread) and some misses (loaded fries). Cocktails read well but weren't our buzz.

Restaurant itself is beautifully designed and the tunes are on point, but they need to fix the signage so people aren't consistently trying to open a locked door next to the table in the window.

After waiting 3 months for a table and coming across the city for it, maybe our group had hyped it up too much, but gutted to say it wasn't the meal we were expecting.

review_text: Been here twice now since reopening and it’s all round 10/10, first time we got the beef rib and oh my god I’ve never had anything like this, was so delicious and huge, brought home leftovers and made a sambo was amazing. The corn ribs are outstanding, flavours are unreal, we got these both times. The birria chips I wouldn’t get again as went very soggy but flavours were good. Nachos were really nice, maybe worth mention the tiny guac portion for €3.50 not really worth it and more cheese sauce would be good, we’re still really good, spicy. Birria tacos sooo comforting, taste was perfect, balance was perfect. The honey soy chicken was also unbelievable, super crispy even with the sauce and pretty spicy. Sticky toffee pudding spring rolls were tasty but they were quite cold when we got them on the first visit. Was dying to give them a second go but was soooo full on our second visit. Drinks were pretty good. Can’t wait to return again when I can manage to get a booking😭 also would love to see takeaway option🩷

formatted_address: 568 S Circular Rd, Rialto, Dublin 8, D08 RF72, Ireland
review_text:
This café has a cozy vibe and friendly staff, which made for a pleasant experience overall. However, there was a small hiccup with my order. I ordered two American pancakes with maple syrup, and while the top pancake was perfectly fluffy and soaked in syrup, the bottom one was surprisingly dry. It felt like the syrup didn’t make it all the way down, which was a bit less tasty than expected.

That said, the atmosphere and service were great, and I’d still recommend giving this place a try. Maybe just ask for extra syrup if you’re ordering pancakes! 🫶🏼

formatted_address: 7 King St N, Dublin, 7, Ireland
review_text:
Stumbled in here after a Taco place I would normally go to was shut - we took a chance, and my goodness it was the right call!

Living in Dublin I find myself craving tacos... A LOT and as a vegetarian, its hard to find ones that hit the spot like those of icons such as birra, chorizo or barbacoa.

Salsa does not have that problem - a delicious blend of sweat potato, mushroom and red pepper, topped with salsa, dressed with fresh herbs and onion and wrapped in that beautiful little corn tortilla. A new go to has been found!

I have walked by the building 1000 times or more, but I shall no longer miss it - what a place and what a delicious lil taco spot to dine in or take out.

Massive congrats to the owner - Tá sé delicious!

formatted_address: Block C, 19 Smithfield, Arran Quay, Dublin, D07 DW40, Ireland
review_text:
Delicious Mexican “fast food” restaurant. In comparison to places in England like BarBurrito and Tortilla, this place served larger quantities and tasted even fresher! The seasoning on the chicken was also much tastier that I’ve had before.

Service was super quick and there was plenty of options ( burrito, burrito bowls, tacos , salads and nachos!) Price is on the higher side compared to what I’m use too but fair for the area. They do student discount too which is great. There is also a good array of soft drinks!

formatted_address: Block C, 19 Smithfield, Arran Quay, Dublin, D07 DW40, Ireland
review_text:
I recently visited with a few friends and it was my first time trying Boojum. I tried their burrito bowl. I got white rice, fajita veggies, carnitas, cheese, lettuce, and sour cream. The portion size was just right, and the fajita veggies were amazing—I’m so glad I chose them over the beans!

The bowl was a bit plain and not very spicy at first, but adding the habanero sauce was a game-changer. It provided the perfect spicy kick that the dish needed.

The staff were friendly, and the atmosphere was nice, making it a pleasant experience overall. I’ll definitely go back to Boojum from time to time! 🌯✨

Also they have student discount!!!

formatted_address: 568 S Circular Rd, Rialto, Dublin 08, D08 RF72, Ireland
review_text:
Genuine and exceptional Mexican street food. Making a reservation is a must; otherwise, it is very unlikely to get a table.
Tacos are delicious, but what truly makes them unique in Dublin is something special: Gorditas and Pambasos.
To highlight: Homemade salsas with the original Mexican street food flavour.
To improve: Customer service. The waitress was quite rude at the checkout, even though we were on time for the following table. It’s essential to maintain a composed demeanour and avoid revealing any stress to customers.
Also, the heating. As far as I can see, it has been a problem since last winter (7 months).

The Mexican wave burger and the kids burger was pretty nice to be honest.

We definitely will not be back and would not recommend in any way.

formatted_address: 1 St Vincent St W, Inchicore, Dublin 8, D08 WT0A, Ireland
review_text: I have been to the other location and we had great service and food but this location is an actual joke. I never write bad reviews but we waited an hour for the food which is supposedly “fast food”. When we went up to tell them that it had been an hour since we ordered (we ordered 10 tacos), they told us that they already made the order and they threw it out. Our buzzer did not go off whatsoever. Someone was at the table with the buzzer on it at all times. It is a Tuesday and they definitely need a better system for things because I have seen past reviews of people waiting an hour for 5 tacos. My partner mentioned that it must have been broken and the person behind the counter was rude and told him it wasn’t but it didn’t buzz. I am not coming back here and I do not recommend it if you are hungry and looking for fast service. They also say on their menu that the tacos come with onion and coriander, ours didn’t and it came out sloppy.

formatted_address: 1 St Vincent St W, Inchicore, Dublin 8, D08 WT0A, Ireland
review_text:
The place looks great and has a convenient setup, as it’s combined with the pub, making it easy to enjoy food and drinks at the same time.

That said, the food was underwhelming. The "al pastor sirloin" didn’t meet expectations and was noticeably inferior to the al pastor served at the other Lupillo location. Additionally, traditional Mexican drinks like horchata or champurrado were unavailable during my visit, which was disappointing.

As for the service, the cashier made a mistake with my order, selecting the wrong type of meat and charging me extra. When I pointed it out, he refunded the 2€, but his attitude was dismissive, which left a bad impression.

Cochinita pibil can be found as tasteless. It is the big piece you can find in the photo attached to my review

formatted_address: 6 Montague St, Dublin, D02 XE65, Ireland
review_text:
Wow what a find. Spanish style small plates with larger options for sharing.

Intimate setting, with some small tables and seats at the bar (where you can see into the kitchen), friendly staff knowledgeable about the menu, and absolutely killer margaritas.

We ordered the Bread with Garlic (should've got 2), Scallops wrapped in belly pork (chefs kiss), Tuna brioche toast (fold it and it eat like a taco) and the star of the show the Chuleton, sharing ribeye.

One of the highlights of our trip.

formatted_address: 6 Montague St, Dublin, D02 XE65, Ireland
review_text:
At the start they offered this shot Chef’s special and it was on the house, which was really nice, very tasty and delicious!

We ordered the:
Achoas - it is tasty and whoever loves anchovies it’s a nice experience.

Tosta de atun - Tuna with a lot of vinagre taste and soaked, it was good but nothing special.

Tortilla Vaga - This is definitely 5 start food, very tasty and well made .

Filete a la pimenta - I found very grease and lack of seasoning and creativity on preparing this dish.

Patadas trufa - very grease too as well as the filete a la pimenta.

The overall food was ok, but the price charged doesn’t align with the food.

Obviously you pay for the place named Michelin 2025 and the environment which is very nice.

There is an option to order a rice as a side, I believe I should’ve ordered that to feel satisfied with the amount of food (which is very pricy and very little and don’t expect anything special but the average )

formatted_address: Unit 4a, the Pavillions, Marine Rd, Dún Laoghaire, Dublin, A96 T27V, Ireland
review_text:
I recently visited Papi Chulo and tried the Vegan Mexican bowl, which included black beans, rice, mushrooms, and a generous portion of cabbage salad by default. You can also choose sauces according to your personal taste.

The restaurant has a cute, cosy, and vibrant atmosphere. The prices are reasonable in relation to the quantity of food served, and the flavours were really enjoyable.

The staff is friendly, and there is a washroom available too. For parking, you can use nearby paid parking, which is just a five-minute walk to the restaurant.
